 time in better\nquality sadhana. That is all that matters.\n\n\n&gt; Number is not really a big consideration.\n\n\nIf, at the same pace, someone doubles the number of repetitions, there is a\ngood chance that their personal progress will also speed up. Though the\nabsolute numbers don&#39;t matter, the relative numbers certainly do.\n\nThe size of the fire matters. The amount of time spent in sadhana matters.\nThe cleanliness of thoughts matters.\n\n\n&gt; at which 5 places do we need to stop\n\n\nThere are three parts in the gayatri mantra. Some people add two more --\n&quot;aum&quot; and &quot;bhuuH...&quot;. Basically, you are asked to stop at the end of each\npart. With 5 parts, you have 5 pauses.\n\nSome people may recite the mantra without pauses (In fact, this is\nspecifically done in some daily rituals like brahma-yagya). In that case,\nthe mantra is recited slightly differently ... there are minor changes to\nthe svaras when there are no pauses.\n\nsasneham,\n\n   ajit\n\n\n\n\nOn Fri, Jan 18, 2013 at 9:36 AM, Krishna M &lt;krishna_m1959@...&gt; wrote:\n\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; &lt;&lt;&lt;&lt;Also, I think it is Brihadaranyaka Upanishat that tells one has to\n&gt; stop Gayatri at 5 places during each chant.&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; Can you please elaborate this point and explain at which 5 places do we\n&gt; need to stop.\n&gt; Also, if possible, it would be helpful if you can please give reference\n&gt; pointers to where this is mentioned in the Brihadaranyaka Upanishad.\n&gt;\n&gt; Thanks in advance\n&gt; Best Regards\n&gt; Krishna\n&gt;\n&gt;    *From:* srikanth_shenoy_k &lt;skshenoy@...&gt;\n&gt; *To:* vedic-wisdom@yahoogroups.com\n&gt; *Sent:* Friday, January 18, 2013 2:11 PM\n&gt; *Subject:* [vedic-wisdom] Re: Gayatri -- Savita\n&gt;  **\n&gt;\n&gt; It depends on one&#39;s anusandhana (i.e. the meaning and the form one\n&gt; meditates upon during Japa).\n&gt; Whats slow for one is just right for another.\n&gt; It takes half a min for me too as Gayatri as one such special Mantra\n&gt; loaded with meanings that has to be &quot;chewed&quot; well and the form has to be\n&gt; fully visualized.\n&gt; Number is not really a big consideration.\n&gt; Getting the state of mind where other thoughts are zero and totally being\n&gt; lost in the mantra and dhyeya rupa becomes important.\n&gt;\n&gt; Also, I think it is Brihadaranyaka Upanishat that tells one has to stop\n&gt; Gayatri at 5 places during each chant. Add that up and 30 seconds is not\n&gt; really a big thing :-)\n&gt;\n&gt; Regards,\n&gt; Srikanth\n&gt;\n&gt; --- In mailto:vedic-wisdom%40yahoogroups.com&lt;vedic-wisdom%40yahoogroups.com&gt;,\n&gt; Ajit Krishnan wrote:\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Dear Hari,\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; Thanks for the nice story.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; It usually takes me 15 minutes to complete 28 times recital silently\n&gt; and\n&gt; &gt; without lip movement. By this timing, I really wonder how much 20-30\n&gt; japas\n&gt; &gt; x 108 times per japa recital must have taken!\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; If we look at traditional texts, the sandhya time starts two ghatikas, or\n&gt; &gt; two nadikas before sunrise, i.e. 48 minutes before sunrise, and it ends\n&gt; &gt; with the onset of sunrise. So, in general, we can assume that about 48\n&gt; &gt; minutes was spent in this particular japa at each sitting. At a moderate\n&gt; &gt; pace, it is possible to complete 500 repetitions in that time.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; I am not suggesting that you speed up, or change anything ... but a half\n&gt; a\n&gt; &gt; minute per repetition is very slow. Personally, at that speed, I would\n&gt; end\n&gt; &gt; up &quot;singing&quot; the mantra.\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; sasneham,\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; ajit\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; On Sun, Jan 13, 2013 at 6:44 AM, Jyotisa Shisya wrote:\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Well Rajarshi,\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Your email triggered some random thoughts in me.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; I have tried to medidate on the Gayatri mantra during my prayer. It\n&gt; &gt; &gt; usually takes me 15 minutes to complete 28 times recital silently and\n&gt; &gt; &gt; without lip movement. By this timing, I really wonder how much 20-30\n&gt; japas\n&gt; &gt; &gt; x 108 times per japa recital must have taken! For the last 3-4 years,\n&gt; &gt; &gt; whenever I wake up first thing in the morning, I see a shining orb of\n&gt; light\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &quot;just&quot; above my head and the opthamologist says everything is just\n&gt; fine. I\n&gt; &gt; &gt; wonder whether this has anything to do with the Gayatri mantra\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; On the topic of medidation, I close with an anecdote about Sri Seshadri\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Swamigal. Once at Ujjain, I saw a dog in samadhi (or so I think!) and\n&gt; it\n&gt; &gt; &gt; was perfectly still for close to 25 minutes! not even a murmur of\n&gt; movement.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &quot;One should not discuss the subject of meditation; one immerse oneself\n&gt; in\n&gt; &gt; &gt; it.&quot;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; One day Avathar Sri Seshadri Swamigal came to Echammal&#39;s house and\n&gt; asked\n&gt; &gt; &gt; her, &quot;What pooja you are doing?&quot; She replied, &quot;I keep Ramana Bhagawan&#39;s\n&gt; &gt; &gt; picture and yours and worship.&quot;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Swami asked her, &quot;How many days will you be doing Pooja? You should\n&gt; sit in\n&gt; &gt; &gt; meditation.&quot; She wanted to know how to meditate? Swami demonstrated it\n&gt; to\n&gt; &gt; &gt; her in the Samadhi from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m. without any movement, like a\n&gt; &gt; &gt; lifeless doll. Echammal and other ladies of the house having completed\n&gt; &gt; &gt; their household tasks sat by His side and observed Swami.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; At 4 o&#39;clock Swami opened His eyes and said, &quot;Did you see, Echammal?\n&gt; This\n&gt; &gt; &gt; is how you have to do meditation.&quot;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; best regards\n&gt; &gt; &gt; Hari\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; On Mon, Jan 7, 2013 at 3:01 PM, rajarshi nandy wrote:\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; **\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Dear Ajit,\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Thanks for the explanations. Very interesting.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; This reminds me of an incident with a good friend of mine. There is an\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; individual I know, who had never chanted the Savitur-Gayatri mantra\n&gt; ever.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; He used to feel, as per his own confession, no special love or\n&gt; attraction\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; for this mantra and being born in a non-brahmin family, there was no\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; religious-cultural occasion where he was formally introduced to this\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; mantra.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; One day while meditating on some Tantrik mantras, he got a random\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; inspiration to meditate on the Gayatri mantra. He had a vague idea of\n&gt; what\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; the Gayatri mantra meant, and no idea at all of correct swara or\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; intonation. So he started chanting, mentally and soundlessly, the\n&gt; Savitur\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Gayatri mantra. Within less than 20-30 japas of the mantra, he\n&gt; felt/saw -\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; and I describe it as he told me - an unbroken steam of tremendous,\n&gt; pure,\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; flood of Golden Light above his head. Like a world above and outside\n&gt; our\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; world. Intensely pure, intensely Divine. The eventual idea, he told\n&gt; me, was\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; to enter into that stream of Light above and see things from that\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; perspective. But as long as there are impurities in the mind and\n&gt; body, it\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; is not possible to enter into that realm easily. The gunas must be in\n&gt; a\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; stable equilibrium. Neither the laziness of Tamas, nor the impatience\n&gt; of\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; rajas is conducive for it, but the stable, illuminating,\n&gt; self-assurance of\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; satwa leading to a deeper equanimity in mind and life is needed.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Apparently, he also realized that there are some Tantrik mantras of Ma\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; which serve a similar purpose as the Gayatri mantra. They take a\n&gt; person to\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; the spiritual planes above.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; So I asked him why did you not continue the meditation or japa of\n&gt; Gayatri\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; mantra, since there was a nice experience. He said it would have\n&gt; pulled him\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; in and he would not have been able to continue the spiritual practices\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; which he was already doing for some time, and leaving something half\n&gt; way is\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; not good.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Reading the explanation your provided below, that is :\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; &quot;We meditate upon that Savitaa (yaH) who impels (prachodayaat) our\n&gt; (naH)\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; thoughts (dhiyaH). He blesses us with subtle eyesight. Without his\n&gt; light,\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; we would not be able to distinguish different objects. This is\n&gt; explained in\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; the Aitaterya Upanishad &quot;The sun, having become eyesight, entered the\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; eyes&quot;. He thus blesses all living beings.&quot;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; .. matches with the description that I had heard from my friend. Quite\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; interesting!\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; -Regards\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Rajarshi\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; *\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; awaktam wyaktimApannam manyantE mAmabuddhayah |\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; 