 to\n&gt; meditate\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; upon.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Whatever is experienced is easy to meditate upon, and that which is\n&gt; not\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; experienced can be difficult to meditate upon. Everyone can meditate\n&gt; upon\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; the light of the Sun. This is why this meaning for the Gayatri mantra\n&gt; is\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; always taken first.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; vareNyam = whatever we can ask / desire. Through all karmas and\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; upaasanaas, whatever fruits we may ask for is vareNyam. &quot;Savitaa&quot; is\n&gt; the\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; fruit of all karmas ... this is taught in the Chandogya Upanishad. [\n&gt; A long\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; explanation follows, which is omitted here ]. We meditate upon the\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; splendor of the sun, which is vareNyam.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; We meditate upon that Savitaa (yaH) who impels (prachodayaat) our\n&gt; (naH)\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; thoughts (dhiyaH). He blesses us with subtle eyesight. Without his\n&gt; light,\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; we would not be able to distinguish different objects. This is\n&gt; explained in\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; the Aitaterya Upanishad &quot;The sun, having become eyesight, entered the\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; eyes&quot;. He thus blesses all living beings.\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; ----\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt; Sent from Windows Mail\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;&gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;   ****\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt; \n\r\n--f46d04016cad49844d04d3964a9a\r\nContent-Type: text/html; charset=ISO-8859-1\r\nContent-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable\r\n\r\n&lt;div&gt;namaste,&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;=A0&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;There are many traditional texts whic=\r\nh encourge us to do 1008 repetitions of the gayatri per sitting, i.e. 3000 =\r\nrepetitions per day. At a 